content:
In an assembly line, I have a call to <pre><code>gethostbyname(...)</code></pre>. I have read that the return value of that function can be a pointer to a <pre><code>hostent</code></pre> structure
(of course, it could be also a null pointer but for my question I need the pointer to the hostent structure)
I also take a look to the hostent structure which is the following:
<pre><code>   typedef struct hostent{
    char FAR *h_name;
    char FAR FAR **h_aliases;
    short h_addrtype;
    short h_length;
    char FAR FAR **h_addr_list;
   } HOSTENT, *PHOSTENT, FAR *LPHOSTENT;


</code></pre>
So, some lines later the following appears:
<pre><code>  mov edx, [eax+0Ch]
</code></pre>
I know that the return value of a function is stored in <pre><code>eax</code></pre>. So, when <pre><code>eax</code></pre> points to <pre><code>hostent</code></pre> structure, then <pre><code>edx</code></pre> must point to one of the <pre><code>hostent</code></pre> structure <pre><code>members</code></pre>, because the offset is <pre><code>0Ch</code></pre>.
To determine which of the member it is, i know that I must count the sizes of the members. And here comes my question:

When I count until I reach the offset <pre><code>0Ch</code></pre>, which of these types I must take? I mean, when you look at the first member, for example:
<pre><code>char FAR *h_name; 
</code></pre>
Is the size of <pre><code>char</code></pre> relevant or the size of <pre><code>FAR</code></pre> ? Or both ?

I hope someone can explain me that.
